      <h2>About</h2>
      <p>This project focuses upon the history of film exhibition, programming and cinemagoing experiences in Laredo, Texas, USA, a U.S.-Mexico bordertown where 95% of its inhabitants are of Mexican ancestry and where Spanish is still widely spoken along with English. Methodologically it is a replica of the Belgian Enlightened City project on cinemagoing in Flanders, applying a triangulation of methods around a cartography of cinemas in Laredo (cf. database on venues, people and exhibition companies); an analysis of film programming (1922 to 1972, sample year per decade); and oral history on audience’s remembrance of film consumption habits in Laredo (1930-1970). The central aim of the project is to make a diachronical analysis of the social role of screen culture in Laredo (1895-1970) as a result of the tensions between commercial and ideological forces and the actual consumption, through a study of cinemas and film consumption in interaction with modernity public space and urbanisation.</p>
    </div>
